{"title_page": "Martina Anderson", "text_new": "{{short description|Irish politician from Northern Ireland|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = \n|name         = Martina Anderson\n|honorific-suffix = \n|image        = Martina Anderson MEP, Strasbourg - Diliff.jpg\n|imagesize    = \n|alt          = \n|caption      = \n|office = [[Member of the European Parliament]] <br/>for [[Northern Ireland (European Parliament constituency)|Northern Ireland]]\n|term_start = 12 June 2012\n|term_end = 31 January 2020\n|predecessor = [[Bairbre de Br\u00fan]]\n|successor = ''Constituency abolished''\n|office2       = [[Junior Minister (Northern Ireland)|Junior Minister]] at the [[Office of the First Minister and Deputy First Minister]]\n|term_start2   = 16 May 2011\n|term_end2     = 11 June 2012\n|alongside2    = [[Jonathan Bell (politician)|Jonathan Bell]]\n|predecessor2  = [[Gerry Kelly]] \n|successor2    = [[Jennifer McCann]] \n|office3      = [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (Northern Ireland)|Member of the Legislative Assembly]] <br/> for [[Foyle (Assembly constituency)|Foyle]]\n|assembly3     = Northern Ireland\n|majority3     = \n|term_start3   = 10 February 2020<ref name=\"mla\">{{cite web|url=http://aims.niassembly.gov.uk/mlas/details.aspx?&aff=2336&per=207&sel=1&ind=0&prv=1 |title=MLA Details: Ms Martina Anderson |publisher=Aims.niassembly.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=2015-10-09}}</ref>\n|term_end3     = \n|predecessor3  = [[Raymond McCartney]]\n|successor3    = \n|term_start4 = 7 March 2007 \n|term_end4 = 11 June 2012\n|predecessor4  = [[Mitchel McLaughlin]]\n|successor4  = [[Maeve McLaughlin]]\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1962|04|16}}<ref name=\"mla\"/>\n|birth_place  = [[Derry]], Northern Ireland<!-- WIKI GUIDELINES PRESENT THE CITY AS \"DERRY\" AND COUNTY AS \"COUNTY LONDONDERRY\" [[Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Ireland-related articles#Derry/Londonderry]] -->\n|death_date   =\n|death_place  = \n|restingplace = \n|birthname    = \n|nationality  = Irish<ref name=\"passport\"/>\n|party        = [[Sinn F\u00e9in]]\n|otherparty   = \n|spouse       = Paul Kavanagh\n|relations    = \n|residence    = \n|alma_mater   = \n|occupation   = \n|profession   = \n|cabinet      = \n|committees   = \n|portfolio    = \n|religion     = \n|signature    = \n|signature_alt= \n|website      ={{url|martinamep.eu/}}\n|footnotes    = \n}}\n'''Martina Anderson''' (born 16 April 1962) is an [[Irish people|Irish]]<ref name=\"passport\">{{cite news |url= https://www.derryjournal.com/news/sinn-fein-anderson-gets-irish-diplomatic-passport-1-6435507 |title= Sinn F\u00e9in: Anderson gets Irish diplomatic passport |date= 2014-11-24 |newspaper= Derry Journal |access-date= 26 June 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190327134525/https://www.derryjournal.com/news/sinn-fein-anderson-gets-irish-diplomatic-passport-1-6435507 |archive-date= 27 March 2019 |url-status= dead }}</ref> politician from [[Northern Ireland]] who was a [[Member of the European Parliament]] (MEP) representing [[Northern Ireland (European Parliament constituency)|Northern Ireland]] for [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] from 2012 to 2020. She became involved in the [[Irish republican]] movement in the late 1970s and is a former [[volunteer (Irish republican)|volunteer]] of the [[Provisional Irish Republican Army]] (IRA). In June 1986, she was convicted of conspiring to cause explosions in 1985 and sentenced to [[life in prison]].<ref name=\"io\" /> She was released 13 years later as a condition of the [[Good Friday Agreement]]<ref name=\"io\">{{cite web | title = Beyond the Wire  | author = | url = http://irelandsown.net/Wire.htm | publisher = Ireland's Own | year = 1996 | accessdate = 21 March 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061209064301/http://irelandsown.net/Wire.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 9 December 2006}}</ref><ref name=\"times\">{{cite news | author = Martin Fletcher | title = 200th release sparks anger | work = [[The Times]] | date = 11 November 1998}}</ref> and subsequently became involved in politics for [[Sinn F\u00e9in]]. She was a [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (Northern Ireland)|Member of the Legislative Assembly]] of Northern Ireland from 2007 to 2012, representing [[Foyle (Assembly constituency)|Foyle]]. She served in the [[Northern Ireland Executive]] as a [[Junior Minister (Northern Ireland)|Junior Minister]] at the [[Office of the First Minister and Deputy First Minister]] from 2011 to 2012. In 2012, she became a Member of the European Parliament, and she was reelected in [[2014 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2014]] and in [[2014 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2019]].\n\n==Biography==\nAnderson was born in the [[Bogside]] in Derry, [[Northern Ireland]], into well-known [[Irish republican]] family.<ref name=\"dj\">{{cite news | author = Kevin Mullan | title = Republican matriarch Betty Anderson to be laid to rest | work = Derry Journal | date = 14 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Friday\u2019s Child: Martina Anderson | work = Derry Journal | date = 5 April 2016}}</ref> Her father was a Protestant.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Donna Deeney|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/sinn-feins-martina-anderson-defends-her-ira-past-38119824.html|title=Sinn F\u00e9in's Martina Anderson defends her IRA past|work=[[Belfast Telegraph]]|date=17 May 2019|access-date=30 November 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> She has six sisters and three brothers, one of whom, Peter, is a former [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] councillor, and her niece is [[Seanad \u00c9ireann|Irish Senator]] and former Foyle MP [[Elisha McCallion]].<ref name=\"dj\"/><ref>{{Cite news|author=Claire Simpson|url=https://www.irishnews.com/news/northernirelandnews/2020/01/31/news/elisha-mccallion-front-runner-to-replace-raymond-mccartney-in-foyle-1830093/|title=Elisha McCallion front-runner to replace Raymond McCartney in Foyle|work= [[Irish News]]|date=31 January 2020|access-date=13 February 2020}}</ref> She was educated at [[St Cecilia's College]] between 1973 and 1980.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Rebecca Black|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/calls-for-explanation-of-pupil-of-the-day-tribute-to-ex-bomber-anderson-36527653.html|title=Calls for explanation of \u2018pupil of the day\u2019 tribute to ex-bomber Anderson|work= Belfast Telegraph|date=25 January 2018|access-date=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nAnderson was arrested aged 18 leaving a furniture store in Derry and charged with possession of a firearm and causing an explosion. She was released on bail after spending two months in [[Armagh (HM Prison)|Armagh Women's Prison]] and fled across the border to [[Buncrana]] in [[County Donegal]].<ref name=\"io\"/><ref name=\"fore\">{{cite news | author = Rory Mooney | title = Martina\u2019s bringing Derry to the fore | work = Derry Journal | date = 20 March 2012}}</ref>\n<!-- what happened in her life during the few years between these events? -->\nAnderson was again arrested on 24 June 1985 at a flat in [[Glasgow]] [[Provisional IRA's Glasgow cell|with four other]] IRA members including Brighton bomber [[Patrick Magee (Irish republican)|Patrick Magee]]. On 11 June 1986, all five were convicted of conspiring to cause explosions in England, although Magee was the only person convicted in relation to the [[Brighton hotel bombing]].<ref name=\"taylor\">{{cite book | last = Taylor | first = Peter | authorlink = Peter Taylor (Journalist) | title = Brits | publisher = [[Bloomsbury Publishing]] | year = 2001 | pages = [https://archive.org/details/brits00pete/page/157 157\u2013159] | doi =  | isbn = 0-7475-5806-X | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/brits00pete/page/157 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Patrick Magee convicted of IRA terrorist attack | author = Gareth Parry | url = https://www.theguardian.com/fromthearchive/story/0,,1235581,00.html | work=[[The Guardian]] | date = 10 June 1986 | accessdate = 21 March 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn 1989, Anderson married fellow prisoner and IRA member Paul Kavanagh at [[Full Sutton (HM Prison)|Full Sutton Prison]]. By 1993, she was one of just two female [[category A prisoners]] in England, the other being fellow republican [[Ella O'Dwyer]].<ref>Sharrock, David, \"Fear and folly in She-Wing\" ''[[The Guardian]]''; 29 December 1993</ref> While at [[Durham (HM Prison)|Durham Prison]], Anderson obtained a [[first-class honours]] degree in [[social science]] from the [[Open University]].<ref name=\"fore\"/> In 1994, she was transferred from Durham to [[Maghaberry (HM Prison)|Maghaberry Prison]] in Northern Ireland.<ref name=\"fore\"/> On 10 November 1998, Anderson was released under the terms of the [[Good Friday Agreement]].<ref name=\"times\"/>\n\n== Political career==\nIn 2007, Anderson was elected to the [[Northern Ireland Assembly]] as a Sinn F\u00e9in member for [[Foyle (Assembly constituency)|Foyle]], along with [[Raymond McCartney]].<ref>{{cite news | title = Northern Ireland election | author = | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/vote2007/nielection/html/258.stm | publisher = [[BBC]] | date = 9 March 2007 | accessdate = 21 March 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2007, Anderson became one of the first Sinn F\u00e9in members to join the [[Northern Ireland Policing Board]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Policing Board \u2013 Martina Anderson MLA |url=http://www.nipolicingboard.org.uk/index/theboard/member.htm?id=6838 |publisher=NI Policing Board |date=31 May 2007 |accessdate=19 April 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080917044430/http://www.nipolicingboard.org.uk/index/theboard/member.htm?id=6838 |archivedate=17 September 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2007, Anderson said she was concerned that large numbers of [[migrant worker]]s from mainly Catholic countries were being classed as 'Catholic/nationalist' in monitoring forms, rather than 'other'.<ref name=\"newsletter.co.uk\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.newsletter.co.uk/news/Sinn-Fein-and-DUP-in.3602650.jp |title=Sinn Fein and DUP in job figures row - Belfast Newsletter |publisher=Newsletter.co.uk |date=2007-12-18 |accessdate=2015-10-10}}</ref> She said \"Given that the entire basis of the legislation around monitoring was put in place to identify imbalances in the workforce between the local Catholic/nationalist and Protestant/unionist communities it is therefore vital that given the addition of migrant workers in the workforce, that they should clearly be categorised as having a community background of 'other'.\"<ref name=\"newsletter.co.uk\"/>\nEmployment monitoring by the [[Equality Commission for Northern Ireland|Equality Commission]] records solely religion, and not political affiliation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.equalityni.org/sections/default.asp?cms=news_Press+Releases&cmsid=1_9&id=90&secid=1_1 |title=ECNI - Equality Commission, Northern Ireland |publisher=Equalityni.org |date=2015-08-30 |accessdate=2015-10-10}}</ref>\n\nShe was selected by Sinn F\u00e9in to fight the [[Foyle (UK Parliament constituency)|Foyle]] constituency at the 2010 Westminster General Election.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.derryjournal.com/politics/Anderson-ready-to--fight.3734291.jp |title=Anderson ready to fight next election |newspaper=Derry Journal |date=2008-01-31 |accessdate=2015-10-10}}</ref> She lost to the SDLP incumbent, [[Mark Durkan]], by 5,000 votes (11% of the vote). In May 2012 it was announced that she would be replacing [[Bairbre de Br\u00fan]], as MEP for [[Northern Ireland (European Parliament constituency)|Northern Ireland]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-18108215|title= Sinn Fein reshuffle as Martina Anderson takes on MEP role|work= BBC News |accessdate=9 May 2012}}</ref> Anderson retained her MEP seat in the 2014 election, topping the poll with 159,813 first-preference votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://electionsireland.org/result.cfm?election=2014E&cons=192 |title=2014 European Election, Northern Ireland First Preference Votes |publisher=ElectionsIreland.org |date=26 May 2014 |accessdate=26 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2019 European Parliament election]]s, Anderson was returned on the fifth ballot, after [[Diane Dodds|Dianne Dodds]] of the [[Democratic Unionist Party|DUP]] and [[Naomi Long]] of [[Alliance Party of Northern Ireland|Alliance]]. After losing her seat due to [[Brexit]], on 10 February 2020 she became MLA for Foyle for a second time, after being selected by Sinn F\u00e9in to replace Raymond McCartney.<ref name=\"mla\"/><ref>{{cite web|title= Martina Anderson 'proud and honoured' to return to Stormont as new Foyle MLA|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-51341485|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC News|date=1 February 2020|accessdate=26 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070310090150/http://www.sinnfeinassembly.com/en/assembly-candidates/entry/5 Official Sinn F\u00e9in biography]\n* [http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/113959/MARTINA_ANDERSON_home.html Martina Anderson on European Parliament website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-par|eu}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Bairbre de Br\u00fan]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n  | title = [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]] for [[Northern Ireland (European Parliament constituency)|Northern Ireland]]\n  | years =  2012 \u2013 2020\n}}\n{{s-non|reason=Constituency abolished}}\n\n{{s-par|ni/ass}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (Northern Ireland)|MLA]] for [[Foyle (Assembly constituency)|Foyle]]\n  | before = [[Mitchel McLaughlin]]\n  | after = [[Maeve McLaughlin]]\n  | years = 2007\u20132012\n}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Raymond McCartney]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n  | title = [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (Northern Ireland)|MLA]] for [[Foyle (Assembly constituency)|Foyle]]\n  | years = 2020-present\n}}